article.description:
Leaving Sacramento Monarchs guard Kara
Lawson alone in 3-point territory is definitely a bad strategy
lately for opponents.
article.headline: Lawson's 3-point shooting dooms Sting
article.linkText: Monarchs win fourth straight after rout of Sting
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Leaving Sacramento Monarchs guard Kara
Lawson alone in 3-point territory is definitely a bad strategy
lately for opponents.

Lawson made five three-pointers Sunday to score 15 points and
help lead the Monarchs to a 76-60 victory over the Charlotte Sting.

Tangela Smith and DeMya Walker also each scored 15 as Sacramento
won its fourth straight.

Lawson, a rookie guard, has been hot lately. She connected on 6
of 7 3-pointers Thursday night and scored a career-high 24 points
in a victory over visiting Los Angeles.

On Sunday, her back-to-back 3-pointers keyed a 12-4 run and gave
Sacramento a 70-52 cushion with 3:44 remaining.

"Kara is playing with a lot of confidence right now," Monarchs
point guard Ticha Penicheiro said. "When she is on the floor, I
try to find her, she's money."

And so are the Monarchs, who after a poor start are making a
serious run at the playoffs. The success comes under Sacramento
interim coach John Whisenant, who has won seven of eight since
replacing Maura McHugh.

Sacramento, in fifth place in the Western Conference at 14-12,
moved to a half-game behind third place Minnesota and Seattle --
both 14-11 -- in the playoff race.

"I feel like we're playing the best basketball of anyone in the
league," said Penicheiro, who had nine points and nine assists.

Andrea Stinson led Charlotte with 21 points as the Sting lost
for the third time in four games and dropped into third place in
the Eastern Conference.

"It's tough to beat good teams on their own court, especially
two nights in a row," Charlotte coach Trudi Lacey said. "We knew
it would be tough the way Sacramento is playing right now.

After falling behind 7-0 to start the game, the Monarchs went on
a 12-2 run and never trailed again. Walker scored nine first-half
points for Sacramento, which led by as many as 17 and went into
halftime ahead 39-29.
